# Maternal Antibody Half-Lives (Oguti et al. method) {#halflife}

The sections above summarise the CordBlood → InfMon2 change as a per-subject
Δlog~10~ and describe its **direction** (decay vs increase). This section re-expresses
the same paired data as an **antibody half-life in days**, using the method of Oguti et
al. (2022), *Vaccine* 40(3):450–458 (doi:10.1016/j.vaccine.2021.12.007), so that the
decay observed here can be placed alongside their pooled, multi-country estimates for the
same six diphtheria–tetanus–pertussis (DTP) antigens.

**Method (as published, adapted to a single study).** For each infant and antigen, Oguti
et al. define the decay rate as the change in **log~2~** antibody titre between the two
samples divided by the number of **days** between them; a one-unit fall on the log~2~
scale is exactly one halving, which is why log~2~ (not the natural log or log~10~) is the
natural scale for half-lives. They then fit, **per antigen**, an intercept-only mixed
model with a **study-specific random intercept**; the mean decay rate is the intercept,
and the **half-life is the reciprocal of the absolute value of that mean rate** (with the
confidence interval obtained by taking reciprocals of the rate CI limits). P-values are
Bonferroni-adjusted across the six antigens, and infants whose titre *increased* over the
interval (a rate ≥ 0, taken to indicate likely infection) are excluded.

Two adaptations are needed here. First, this document works on the **log~10~** scale, so
each paired Δlog~10~ is converted to Δlog~2~ by multiplying by $1/\log_{10}(2) \approx
3.322$. Second, this is a **single study**, so the study-level random intercept of the
meta-analysis has nothing to cluster; the model reduces to an **intercept-only linear
model per antigen** (equivalently, the mean per-infant decay rate with a t-based 95% CI),
which is exactly what the Oguti model collapses to when there is one study. Only the
**total antigen-specific IgG** analyte is used, matching the transplacentally transferred
IgG that Oguti et al. measured.

The per-infant sampling interval is the **exact number of days between the cord-blood
draw and the 2-month (pre-primary) draw**, computed for each infant from the sample
receipt dates in the study database (`INTERVAL_DAYS_BY_SUBJECT`; see
`code/build_interval_days.R`). Because each infant's decay rate is divided by that
infant's own interval, the half-lives are on a true per-day footing and require no
assumed constant. The few infants whose 2-month receipt date is missing or unparseable
fall back to the cohort-median interval so they still contribute to the antigen-specific
means; this fallback affects only a handful of infants and does not change any
between-group comparison.

```{r halflife-setup, include=FALSE}
## =====================================================================
## Maternal antibody half-lives — Oguti et al. (2022) method
## Vaccine 40(3):450-458. doi:10.1016/j.vaccine.2021.12.007
## ---------------------------------------------------------------------
##  decay rate_i = (log2 titre_InfMon2 - log2 titre_CordBlood) / days_i
##  per antigen: intercept-only model -> mean rate + 95% CI
##  half-life = 1 / |mean rate| ; CI = reciprocals of |rate CI|
##  p-values Bonferroni-adjusted across the six antigens
##  infants with a non-negative rate (increase = likely infection) excluded
## =====================================================================

LOG10_TO_LOG2        <- 1 / log10(2)     # ~3.321928 ; log2 delta = log10 delta * this
HL_ANALYTE           <- "IgG"            # total antigen-specific IgG (the transplacental antibody)
HL_ANTIGENS          <- c("DT", "TT", "PT", "FHA", "PRN", "FIM")  # six DTP antigens
HL_EXCLUDE_INCREASES <- TRUE             # match Oguti et al. (increase = likely infection)
N_BONF               <- length(HL_ANTIGENS)

## ---- Days between CordBlood and InfMon2 (exact, per infant) ----------
## The serology object (`ebaa_extra`) carries no sampling date, so the exact
## cord -> 2-month interval is supplied per infant from the sample-receipt
## dates via INTERVAL_DAYS_BY_SUBJECT (built by code/build_interval_days.R;
## columns: subject_accession, interval_days). If that object is not already
## in the session, load it from data/INTERVAL_DAYS_BY_SUBJECT.RData.
##
## NOMINAL_INTERVAL_DAYS is retained ONLY as a per-subject fallback for the
## few infants whose 2-month receipt date is missing/unparseable, so they
## still contribute to the antigen means. Because each infant's rate is
## divided by that infant's own interval, the half-lives are on a true
## per-day footing; the fallback touches only a handful of infants and does
## not affect any between-group comparison.
NOMINAL_INTERVAL_DAYS <- 8.7 * 7         # 60.9 d = 8.7 wk (Oguti Table 1 pooled median; fallback only)

## Make the interval table available (load if not already in the session).
if (!exists("INTERVAL_DAYS_BY_SUBJECT")) {
  .iv_path <- tryCatch(find_proj_file("data/INTERVAL_DAYS_BY_SUBJECT.RData"),
                       error = function(e) NULL)
  if (!is.null(.iv_path) && file.exists(.iv_path)) {
    load(.iv_path)                       # restores INTERVAL_DAYS_BY_SUBJECT
  }
}

if (exists("INTERVAL_DAYS_BY_SUBJECT") &&
    is.data.frame(INTERVAL_DAYS_BY_SUBJECT) &&
    all(c("subject_accession", "interval_days") %in% names(INTERVAL_DAYS_BY_SUBJECT))) {
  .iv_tbl <- INTERVAL_DAYS_BY_SUBJECT[, c("subject_accession", "interval_days")]
  .iv_tbl$subject_accession <- as.character(.iv_tbl$subject_accession)  # match join key type
  .iv_tbl$interval_days     <- as.numeric(.iv_tbl$interval_days)
  .iv_med <- stats::median(.iv_tbl$interval_days, na.rm = TRUE)
  INTERVAL_IS_NOMINAL <- FALSE
  INTERVAL_SOURCE <- sprintf(
    "exact per-infant cord -> 2-month interval from sample-receipt dates (n = %d infants, median %.1f d)",
    sum(is.finite(.iv_tbl$interval_days)), .iv_med)
} else {
  .iv_tbl <- NULL
  INTERVAL_IS_NOMINAL <- TRUE
  INTERVAL_SOURCE <- sprintf(paste0("nominal constant of %.1f days -- INTERVAL_DAYS_BY_SUBJECT was not ",
                                    "found in the session or under data/"), NOMINAL_INTERVAL_DAYS)
}

## ---- Per-subject x antigen log2 decay rate (per day) ----------------
hl_dat <- paired %>%
  dplyr::filter(analyte == HL_ANALYTE, antigen %in% HL_ANTIGENS) %>%
  dplyr::transmute(subject_accession = as.character(subject_accession), antigen,
                   delta_log2 = delta * LOG10_TO_LOG2)

if (INTERVAL_IS_NOMINAL) {
  hl_dat$interval_days <- NOMINAL_INTERVAL_DAYS
  N_INTERVAL_MATCHED  <- 0L
  N_INTERVAL_FALLBACK <- dplyr::n_distinct(hl_dat$subject_accession)
} else {
  hl_dat <- hl_dat %>%
    dplyr::left_join(.iv_tbl, by = "subject_accession")
  ## Count infants using an exact interval vs the median fallback (before filling)
  .iv_used <- hl_dat %>%
    dplyr::distinct(subject_accession, interval_days) %>%
    dplyr::summarize(matched  = sum(is.finite(interval_days)),
                     fallback = sum(!is.finite(interval_days)))
  N_INTERVAL_MATCHED  <- .iv_used$matched
  N_INTERVAL_FALLBACK <- .iv_used$fallback
  ## Fall back to the cohort-median interval (not the Oguti nominal) for the
  ## few infants without a usable date, so the fallback matches this cohort.
  .fallback_days <- if (is.finite(.iv_med)) .iv_med else NOMINAL_INTERVAL_DAYS
  hl_dat <- hl_dat %>%
    dplyr::mutate(interval_days = ifelse(is.finite(interval_days),
                                         interval_days, .fallback_days))
}

hl_dat <- hl_dat %>%
  dplyr::mutate(rate = delta_log2 / interval_days) %>%
  dplyr::filter(is.finite(rate))

HL_ANTIGENS_PRESENT <- intersect(HL_ANTIGENS, unique(hl_dat$antigen))
HL_ANTIGENS_MISSING <- setdiff(HL_ANTIGENS, HL_ANTIGENS_PRESENT)

## Count how many infants are dropped by the "exclude increases" rule
hl_excl <- hl_dat %>%
  dplyr::group_by(antigen) %>%
  dplyr::summarize(n_all = dplyr::n(),
                   n_increase = sum(rate >= 0),
                   n_used = sum(rate < 0),
                   .groups = "drop")

hl_use <- if (HL_EXCLUDE_INCREASES) dplyr::filter(hl_dat, rate < 0) else hl_dat

## ---- Per-antigen intercept-only fit -> half-life + 95% CI -----------
fit_one <- function(d) {
  r <- d$rate[is.finite(d$rate)]
  n <- length(r)
  if (n < 3 || stats::sd(r) == 0) return(NULL)
  fit <- stats::lm(r ~ 1)
  est <- unname(stats::coef(fit)[1])
  ci  <- unname(stats::confint(fit)[1, ])
  p   <- stats::coef(summary(fit))[1, 4]        # H0: mean rate = 0 (no decay)
  hl_ci <- sort(1 / abs(ci))
  data.frame(n = n, rate = est, rate_lo = ci[1], rate_hi = ci[2],
             half_life = 1 / abs(est), hl_lo = hl_ci[1], hl_hi = hl_ci[2],
             p_raw = p, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
}

hl_est <- do.call(rbind, lapply(split(hl_use, hl_use$antigen), function(d) {
  f <- fit_one(d); if (is.null(f)) return(NULL)
  cbind(antigen = d$antigen[1], f, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
}))
if (is.null(hl_est)) hl_est <- data.frame()
if (nrow(hl_est)) hl_est$p_bonf <- pmin(1, hl_est$p_raw * N_BONF)

## ---- Published reference values (Oguti et al. 2022, Fig 1; total IgG) ----
oguti_ref <- data.frame(
  antigen       = c("PT", "PRN", "FHA", "FIM", "TT", "DT"),
  antigen_label = c("Pertussis toxoid", "Pertactin", "FHA",
                    "Fimbriae 2/3", "Tetanus", "Diphtheria"),
  oguti_n  = c(549L, 1103L, 654L, 1022L, 1021L, 620L),
  oguti_hl = c(30.0, 35.1, 31.3, 33.5, 28.7, 33.1),
  oguti_lo = c(24.8, 30.7, 28.3, 31.5, 24.4, 27.5),
  oguti_hi = c(37.8, 41.1, 35.1, 35.8, 35.0, 41.8),
  stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

## ---- This study vs Oguti et al. -------------------------------------
hl_cmp <- if (nrow(hl_est)) {
  merge(hl_est, oguti_ref, by = "antigen", all.x = TRUE) %>%
    dplyr::mutate(
      ci_overlap  = !(hl_hi < oguti_lo | hl_lo > oguti_hi),
      in_oguti_ci = half_life >= oguti_lo & half_life <= oguti_hi,
      diff_days   = half_life - oguti_hl) %>%
    dplyr::arrange(match(antigen, oguti_ref$antigen))
} else data.frame()

## Headline diagnostics for the narrative (all data-derived)
hl_overall_range <- if (nrow(hl_est))
  sprintf("%.1f (%s) to %.1f (%s)",
          min(hl_est$half_life), hl_est$antigen[which.min(hl_est$half_life)],
          max(hl_est$half_life), hl_est$antigen[which.max(hl_est$half_life)]) else "n/a"
n_overlap  <- if (nrow(hl_cmp)) sum(hl_cmp$ci_overlap, na.rm = TRUE) else 0L
n_in_ci    <- if (nrow(hl_cmp)) sum(hl_cmp$in_oguti_ci, na.rm = TRUE) else 0L
n_compared <- if (nrow(hl_cmp)) sum(!is.na(hl_cmp$oguti_hl)) else 0L
mean_absdiff <- if (nrow(hl_cmp)) round(mean(abs(hl_cmp$diff_days), na.rm = TRUE), 1) else NA_real_
