## By maternal arm

```{r interp-arm, results='asis'}
cat(sprintf("Per-antigen decay Δ by arm: total IgG (%s); IgG1 (%s). ",
  arm_decay("IgG"), arm_decay("IgG1")))
g_ig <- { ds <- decay_all %>% dplyr::filter(antigen %in% ANTIGEN_ORDER, analyte == "IgG", arm != "Pooled")
  abs(stats::median(ds$med_delta[ds$arm == "TdaP"], na.rm = TRUE) - stats::median(ds$med_delta[ds$arm == "TT"], na.rm = TRUE)) }
g_ig1 <- { ds <- decay_all %>% dplyr::filter(antigen %in% ANTIGEN_ORDER, analyte == "IgG1", arm != "Pooled")
  abs(stats::median(ds$med_delta[ds$arm == "TdaP"], na.rm = TRUE) - stats::median(ds$med_delta[ds$arm == "TT"], na.rm = TRUE)) }
maxgap  <- max(c(g_ig, g_ig1), na.rm = TRUE)
similar <- is.finite(maxgap) && maxgap < 0.05
cat(sprintf("The arms are **%s** (largest total-IgG/IgG1 decay-\\u0394 gap %.3f log10). ",
  ifelse(similar, "closely matched", "modestly different"), maxgap))
cat(ifelse(similar,
  paste0("Parallel decay across arms is the expected result: catabolism is set by the antibody, not the ",
         "vaccine; the vaccine determines the cord starting level, not the rate of waning.\n\n"),
  paste0("Because catabolic rate is antibody-driven, a gap of this size most plausibly reflects different ",
         "starting (cord) levels and antigen mix between arms rather than a different decay process; the ",
         "per-arm figures (Table 8, Figure A1) are the check.\n\n")))
```

## Reliability of each estimand

Total IgG and IgG1 decay are the most reliable estimands from the CordBlood → InfMon2 comparison:
total IgG comes from the RIVM ELISA path and does not pass through the bead-array cross-plate
normalisation, IgG1 is the dominant transferred subclass, and the two agree. The normalised
IgG2/IgG3/IgG4 deltas are usable but small; any per-antigen positive residual should be treated as
antigen-specific (a floor or batch signature) rather than as a uniform subclass trend or as infant
antibody production. Effector-function, FcR-binding, and B-memory readouts (ADCD, ADCP, ADNP,
FcgR2a, FcgR3b, Bmem) were not assayed in CordBlood, so their birth-to-2-month trajectory is
unobserved in this dataset.

## What would confirm or refine this interpretation

- **Examine absolute cord-blood distributions for any antigen with a residual subclass increase** — if
  a large fraction of infants sit near the assay floor, the floor-effect explanation is confirmed.
- **Check whether residual subclass increases correlate with cord-blood level** (regression to the
  mean): the lowest cord values showing the largest positive deltas points to a floor effect.
- **Read Tables 7–8 and Figure A1** to confirm decay is parallel across arms rather than relying on the
  pooled medians alone.
- **Correlate per-subject mean delta with plate/batch metadata** (Figure 3): residual plate-level
  clustering would indicate an incomplete cross-plate correction for some plates.

